claims:
1. A method for managing water deficit stress in plants comprising:
a) measuring the temperature of a target plant;
b) measuring the atmospheric humidity in the vicinity of said plant;
c) comparing said temperature of said plant with a water-deficit stress setpoint temperature for said plant that is defined as the approximate plant temperature that is associated with a predetermined plant stress level, wherein said predetermined plant stress level is not optimal for metabolism of said plant, and determining if said humidity is restrictive to plant cooling; and
1) returning to said step (a) if either: (i) the measured plant temperature is less than or equal to said setpoint temperature, or (ii) said humidity is restrictive to plant cooling; or
2) generating and displaying an irrigation signal or initiating irrigation if the measured plant temperature is greater than said setpoint temperature and said humidity is not restrictive to plant cooling.

17. An apparatus for use in managing the irrigation of plants comprising:
a) a temperature measurement device capable of measuring the temperature of one or more plants;
b) an atmospheric humidity sensor; and
c) a microprocessor in communication with said temperature measurement device and said humidity sensor, said microprocessor effective to receive and compare the measured plant temperature to a water-deficit stress setpoint temperature, and for comparing the measured humidity to a limiting humidity value;
wherein said water-deficit stress setpoint temperature for said plant is defined as the approximate plant temperature that is associated with a predetermined plant stress level, and further wherein said predetermined plant stress level is not optimal for metabolism of said plant.
